snippet.textDisplay: A reminder that luck is a factor. You’ll hear many times, especially from the Big Three, that’s luck was a factor is some of their important matches. But what’s more important is that they also create opportunities that allow for the roll of the die. Sometimes it works, and sometimes it doesn’t. What Federer does well, is to put the opponent in a position where they have to make a shot. Then again, so do all the best players in the world. Luck certainly has benefited the Big Three in some of their important matches.

snippet.textDisplay: Federer is very good tennis player.  However in my analysis,  he did not really got injured during the match.  The way he played and moved in the fourth and final set does't look that he has a serious injury.  He misses a lot because of the strong serve and return of Sandgren,  it gives a lot pressures to him  as a result it loses his timing.    I guess, but not really sure ... Fed uses the medical time-out to break the rhythm and pressure from his opponent.   It was too long actually,  it should be 3 minutes only but the medical time-out lasted for 8 minutes.    But nevertheless Fed is still a great tennis player.  If he's really injured,  he will full-out during the match with Djokovic.  Because Injured muscle is really difficult to recover in one day.  Worst it will start to cause pain.  If ... that injury is really true ... because he was away from the court for 8 minutes.
